 See if there is some data there that you might use for some interesting
 project.
 It is of course not OK to repeat an analysis from the book, you have to
 come up with your own application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Topic classification
\series default
.
 Online newspaper place their articles under different fixed topics.
 For example The New York Times (nytimes.com) classifies their articles under
 topics such as 
\emph on
Technology
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Science
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Health
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Sports
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Arts
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Style
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Travel
\emph default
 etc.
 Fetch a sample of webpages from the newspaper, and build a classifier that
 is able to predict the articles' topics.
 This is just one example of topic classification, I am sure that you can
 think of many similar projects.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Contact person: 
\series bold
Mattias Villani
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Data from 
\series bold
Twitter
\series default
 or other similar microblogs/social networks (Facebook, Google+, LinkedIn
 etc etc) is a good source of text data, which is relatively easily accessible.
 You can also use other type of information from Twitter, such as information
 on who follows who, and who retweets who, and so on.
 There are already books written on how to mine text from social networks
 such as Twitter (see for example http://shop.oreilly.com/product/0636920010203.do).
 
